ful Philadelphia family, his personal life and eccentricities, his reform achievements, his place in Mormon history, and his career as a Civil War general. Further, the book revises previous understandings of nineteenth-century reform, showing how Kane and likeminded others fused Democratic Party ideology, anti-evangelicalism, and romanticism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAbolitionistsxBiographyxUnited States. 0aMormon ChurchxHistoryx19th centuryxUnited States. 0aMormon pioneersxHistoryx19th centuryxUtah. 0aMormonsxHistoryx19th centuryxWest (U.S.). 0aSocial reformersxBiographyxUnited States. 0aSoldiersxBiographyxUnited States. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Philosophers.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300153262423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300153262.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles